AND.description: If both points are TRUE or ON, then this will proceed to the then condition.  If either is FALSE, then the condition will not be met.
AND.example: IF("POINT.1" .AND. "POINT.2") THEN GOTO 4300" -> If and only if both points are true, then the condition will proceed.  Otherwise, the next line will execute and trace.

COM.description: The complement function.  Hi, you're looking great! Actually, this produces the boolean opposite of a 0 or 1.  So, if "POINT.2" is equal to 1, this function would make "POINT.1" equal to 0.
COM.example: "POINT.1" = COM("POINT.2") -> If "POINT.2" = 1, then "POINT.1" will be set to 0.

COS.description: The COSINE function.  Like when you can't afford NYC rent and don't make 50 times the rent in annual salary, and your parents have to sign the lease too, so that the landlord actually gives you the place! Nah, it's the Pythagorus kind of cosine.
COS.example: "POINT.1" = COS("POINT.2") -> If "POINT.2" = PI/2, then "POINT.1" will be set to 1.

NAND.example: IF("POINT.1" .NAND. "POINT.2") THEN GOTO 4300" -> Only if both of the points is FALSE, then the condition will proceed.  Otherwise, the next line will execute and trace.

ROOT.description: The ROOT function. This takes the Nth root ("POINT.2") of a number ("POINT.1").  This takes decimal roots and numbers as well.
ROOT.example: "POINT.3" = "POINT.1" .ROOT. "POINT.2") -> If "POINT.2" = 2 and "POINT.1" is 8, then "POINT.3" will be 3.

SIN.description: The SINE function. The opposite over the hypotenus.
SIN.example: "POINT.1" = SIN("POINT.2") -> If "POINT.2" = PI, then "POINT.1" will be set to 1.

SQRT.description: The SQUARE ROOT function. This takes the 2th root ("POINT.2") of a number ("POINT.1").
SQRT.example: "POINT.3" = "POINT.1" .SQRT. "POINT.2") -> If "POINT.2" = 2 and "POINT.1" is 4, then "POINT.3" will be 2.

TABLE.description: A table statement makes a linear interpolation between the x points and y points, given the input variable, and maps to the ouptut variable.
TABLE.example: TABLE($LOC1, $LOC2, 0, 0, 10, 100) -> if $LOC1 is 0, $LOC2 would be 0.  If $LOC1 is 5, $LOC2 would be 50.  If $LOC1 is 10, $LOC2 would be 100.  Also,  if $LOC1 is -2, $LOC2 would be 0, and  if $LOC1 is 15, $LOC2 would be 100.

TAN.description: The TAN function. It get's you bronzed.  The adjacent over the opposite.
TAN.example: "POINT.1" = TAN("POINT.2") -> If "POINT.2" = PI/4, then "POINT.1" will be set to 1.
